---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import Sidebar from "../../components/Sidebar.astro";
import Card from "../../components/Card.astro";
---

<Base title="Documentation" description="Mire documentation — tutorials, how-to guides, reference, and explanation, organized the Diátaxis way.">
  <div class="docs">
    <Sidebar currentId="" />
    <article class="docs__main">
      <p class="docs__kicker">Documentation</p>
      <h1 class="docs__title">Learn Mire</h1>
      <p class="docs__lead">
        New here? Start with the tutorials. Solving a specific problem? Jump to a how-to
        guide. Looking something up? The reference has it. Want the reasoning? Read the
        explanations.
      </p>
      <div class="prose">
        <div class="card-grid">
          <Card href="/docs/tutorials/your-first-app/" kicker="learning" title="Tutorials">
            Hands-on lessons that build a working app from nothing. Start here.
          </Card>
          <Card href="/docs/how-to/handle-input/" kicker="tasks" title="How-to guides">
            Focused recipes for a specific job: input, theming, overlays, mouse, text, images.
          </Card>
          <Card href="/docs/reference/widgets/" kicker="lookup" title="Reference">
            Dry, complete descriptions: widgets, layout nodes, the API, styling, the agent layer.
          </Card>
          <Card href="/docs/explanation/the-loop/" kicker="understanding" title="Explanation">
            The reasoning: the render pipeline, why MVU for terminals, the region model.
          </Card>
        </div>
        <h2>Install</h2>
        <p>Mire is a single NuGet package targeting <code>net10.0</code>:</p>
        <pre class="astro-code"><code>dotnet add package Mire</code></pre>
        <p>Then follow <a href="/docs/tutorials/your-first-app/">Your first app</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Base>
